  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Top quality care&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;I had a hysterectomy earlier this month following a diagnosis of endometriosis earlier this year. From the initial referral to Tameside, throughout investigative procedures, including an ultra-sound then followed by an MRI scan a few weeks later, as well as all consultant appointments, I felt that I was fully informed in all areas of my care at all times. When I took the decision to opt for surgery I felt that I was able to make the decision having been patiently talked through all my options. This level of care continued throughout the time leading up to surgery, during my stay in the hospital on the ISGU ward and is still happening post operation. From secretary to nurse to consultant, any member of the team who has been part of my treatment has been informative, respectful of my wishes and supportive of any decisions I have made. 

My criticism does not lie with any of the staff who administered my care. However during my stay on the ward, there were several occasions where it was apparent that the very basic of resources were in short supply; pillows, blood pressure monitors and trolleys to hang a drip from. A nurses job is hard enough without having to look for items which should on hand pretty much all the time. 

Despite this my care has been amazing. Thank you. &lt;/CommentText&gt;
